        cons: ['Because the platform is explicitly optimized for parsing algorithms, the resulting exported formats are structurally incredibly rigid, boring, and highly standardized; a graphic designer seeking to showcase a wildly creative, highly aesthetic visual layout will hate the platform', 'Blindly utilizing the AI to hallucinate highly complex, metrics-driven bullet points can easily induce the user to accidentally lie (e.g., claiming they generated "40% revenue growth" when they did not), leading to catastrophic embarrassment during the actual human interview', 'The platform relies heavily on the assumption that HR algorithms operate in a specific way; if a specific startup manually reads all PDFs rather than parsing them, the highly keyword-injected robot-language might seem unnatural to the human reader'],
        pricing_overview: '<p>Rezi operates a highly direct B2C Freemium SaaS model. The Free tier allows a desperate job seeker to build and export standard resumes, ensuring high platform virality. However, to unlock the massive power of the "AI Writer," the highly aggressive Job Description Keyword Targeting, and unlimited AI Cover Letters, users must purchase specific "AI Credits" or subscribe to the premium monthly tier.</p>',
        comparison_summary: '<p>Rezi battles in the highly stressful, chaotic consumer "Career-Tech" sector against tools like Resume Worded, Kickresume, and standard Zety templates. Kickresume focuses heavily on visual aesthetic and design. Resume Worded operates primarily as an auditor of existing resumes. Rezi differentiates itself as the *Absolute ATS Weapon*. It is not built to be pretty; its relentless, aggressive engineering focus is purely to mathematically force its way through corporate filtering software using generative AI, making it the supreme tactical engine for landing corporate interviews.</p>'
